    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-22T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-22T10:00:00-05:00" n="849"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d849">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867.24/450: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kelley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-22T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 22, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1052. Department’s 461, September 23, paragraph 1. I have ascertained that
                    Turkish-Swedish negotiations for charter of three Swedish vessels by Turkey have
                    broken down because Germans have refused to allow these ships to leave Baltic.
                    It is opinion of Foreign Office that there is no possibility of negotiations
                    being renewed.</p>
                <p>Department will recall that in chrome negotiations the Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs<note n="65" xml:id="d849fn65">Numan Menemencioğlu.</note> requested
                    British to let him have 5,000 tons of chrome for delivery to Sweden in
                    connection with charter of Swedish vessels. It appears that Swedes insisted upon
                    delivery of chrome as soon as first Swedish vessel arrived in Turk waters. Turks
                    now admit their belief that chrome demand had been made at German instigation
                    and that chrome would probably have gone to Germany.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kelley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
